      <!-- ────────── SYNCING ────────── -->
      <section id="syncing">
        <h2>Syncing with your team</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">Your repo lives on your machine. "Remote" is the shared copy on GitHub. These commands move work between the two.</p>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git pull" data-search="git pull download latest merge refresh shared workbook">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git pull</span><span class="cmd-desc">Download latest changes and merge them in</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Hit Refresh on the shared workbook to grab whatever everyone else has been doing while you were gone.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git push" data-search="git push upload saves remote shared drive">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git push</span><span class="cmd-desc">Upload your saves to the remote</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Save your stuff back to the shared drive so the rest of the team can actually see what you did.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git fetch" data-search="git fetch check new versions exist without downloading">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git fetch</span><span class="cmd-desc">Check if new versions exist, but don't download yet</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Peeking at the shared drive like "anyone save anything new?" without actually opening it.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git pull origin main" data-search="git pull origin main latest main current branch master sheet working tab">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git pull origin main</span><span class="cmd-desc">Bring the latest main into your current branch</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Grab whatever's new on the master sheet and paste it into yours. Stay up to date.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="Pull Request (PR)" data-search="pull request PR review changes merging email boss review master copy">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">Pull Request (PR)</span><span class="cmd-desc">Ask others to review your changes before merging</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Sending your boss an email: "Hey, I tweaked some stuff &mdash; mind taking a look before I put it in the main sheet?"</div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ────────── COMBINING WORK ────────── -->
      <section id="combining">
        <h2>Combining work</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">When you're done working on a branch, you bring it back together with the main line. Here's how.</p>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git merge main" data-search="git merge main branch changes copy paste different cells same cell pick">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git merge main</span><span class="cmd-desc">Bring another branch's changes into yours</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Copy from the main sheet into yours. Changed different cells? Great, both kept. Same cell? Excel goes "uh, which one do you want?"</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git rebase main" data-search="git rebase main replay changes latest rewrite version history">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git rebase main</span><span class="cmd-desc">Replay your changes on top of the latest main</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Sneakily rewrite your version history so it looks like you started from the latest copy all along. Nobody needs to know.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git cherry-pick abc123" data-search="git cherry-pick abc123 copy one specific commit edit another sheet tab">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git cherry-pick abc123</span><span class="cmd-desc">Copy one specific commit from another branch</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Reach into another tab and grab just that one specific edit. Leave everything else alone.</div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ────────── MERGE CONFLICTS ────────── -->
      <section id="conflicts">
        <h2>Merge conflicts</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">When two people change the same thing, Git can't decide which version to keep. It asks you.</p>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="Merge conflict" data-search="merge conflict both sides changed same lines cell highlights which value">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">Merge conflict</span><span class="cmd-desc">Both sides changed the same lines</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> You and Karen both edited cell B7. Excel throws its hands up: "I can't pick &mdash; you two figure it out."</div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout">
          Don't panic. A conflict isn't an error — it's Git asking for your opinion. Open the file, pick the version you want, save, then <code>git add</code> + <code>git commit</code>.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ────────── I MESSED UP ────────── -->
      <section id="messed-up">
        <h2>I messed up</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">Everyone does. Git has several levels of "undo" — from gentle to nuclear.</p>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git stash" data-search="git stash temporarily set aside uncommitted changes cut clipboard switch tabs">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git stash</span><span class="cmd-desc">Temporarily set aside uncommitted changes</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Ctrl+X your half-done work, go deal with something else, then Ctrl+V it back when you're ready.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git stash pop" data-search="git stash pop bring back stashed changes paste clipboard">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git stash pop</span><span class="cmd-desc">Bring back stashed changes</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Ctrl+V. Your stuff's back right where you left it.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git reset --soft HEAD~1" data-search="git reset soft HEAD undo last commit keep changes files undo save as keep edits cells">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git reset --soft HEAD~1</span><span class="cmd-desc">Undo the last commit, but keep the changes in your files</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Undo the last Save As, but your edits are still sitting right there in the cells. No harm done.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git reset --hard HEAD~1" data-search="git reset hard HEAD undo last commit revert all files undo save ctrl z previous version">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git reset --hard HEAD~1</span><span class="cmd-desc">Undo the last commit AND revert all files</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Nuke it. Undo the save AND Ctrl+Z everything back to before. Your edits? Gone. Like it never happened.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout">
          <code>--soft</code> is safe. <code>--hard</code> is destructive. If you're not sure, always use <code>--soft</code> first.
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git revert abc123" data-search="git revert abc123 new commit undoes previous deleting version history new save manually reverses">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git revert abc123</span><span class="cmd-desc">Create a new commit that undoes a previous one</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> Don't delete history &mdash; that's shady. Instead, make a new save that carefully undoes the damage. Everyone can see what happened.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="cmd-card" data-cmd="git merge --abort" data-search="git merge abort cancel merge in progress nevermind undo paste go back">
          <div class="cmd-card-header"><span class="cmd-name">git merge --abort</span><span class="cmd-desc">Cancel a merge that's in progress</span></div>
          <div class="cmd-analogy"><span class="cmd-analogy-label">Excel</span> "Nope nope nope, undo everything, go back to before I tried to paste. Pretend this never happened."</div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ────────── ALL COMMANDS ────────── -->
      <section id="all-commands">
        <h2>All commands</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">The full cheatsheet in one table. Ctrl+F friendly.</p>

        <table class="cheatsheet-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Command</th><th>What it does</th><th>Excel analogy</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Getting Started</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git init</td><td>Create a new repository</td><td>Fresh empty spreadsheet. Pure potential.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git clone</td><td>Download a copy of someone's repo</td><td>Grab your coworker's file from the shared drive</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Saving Your Work</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git add filename.txt</td><td>Select which changes to include in the next save</td><td>"I only want to save these cells right now"</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git add .</td><td>Select all changes</td><td>Ctrl+A, grab everything, throw it in the save</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git commit</td><td>Save a snapshot with a note</td><td>Save As + scribble a note about what you did</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git commit -m "msg"</td><td>Save with a one-line description</td><td>That little comment box in Save As</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Checking What's Going On</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git status</td><td>See what's changed and what's staged</td><td>That asterisk nagging you about unsaved changes</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git log</td><td>See the full save history</td><td>File &rarr; Version History, scroll through everything</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git diff</td><td>See exactly what changed, line by line</td><td>Track Changes &mdash; red gone, green new</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Branches</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git branch</td><td>List all branches</td><td>Glance at your sheet tabs at the bottom</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git branch new-name</td><td>Create a new branch (stay where you are)</td><td>Right-click, Duplicate, leave it sitting there</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git checkout -b new-name</td><td>Create a new branch and switch to it</td><td>Duplicate a tab and start working in the copy</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git switch branch-name</td><td>Switch to an existing branch</td><td>Click a different tab. That's it.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git branch -d name</td><td>Delete a branch</td><td>Right-click, delete. Gone.</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Combining Work</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git merge main</td><td>Bring another branch's changes into yours</td><td>Copy &amp; paste from main. Same cell? "Which one?"</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git rebase main</td><td>Replay changes on top of latest main</td><td>Sneakily rewrite history. Nobody needs to know.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git cherry-pick abc123</td><td>Copy one specific commit</td><td>Grab just that one edit from another tab</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Merge conflict</td><td>Both sides changed the same lines</td><td>You and Karen both edited B7. "Figure it out."</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Syncing with Others</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git pull</td><td>Download latest changes and merge</td><td>Hit Refresh, grab what everyone else did</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git push</td><td>Upload your saves to the remote</td><td>Save it back so the team can see your work</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git fetch</td><td>Check for new versions without downloading</td><td>"Anyone save anything new?" (without opening it)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git pull origin main</td><td>Bring latest main into current branch</td><td>Grab what's new on the master sheet, paste into yours</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Pull Request (PR)</td><td>Ask others to review before merging</td><td>"Hey boss, mind checking this before I merge?"</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Undo &amp; Recovery</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git stash</td><td>Set aside uncommitted changes</td><td>Ctrl+X your half-done work for later</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git stash pop</td><td>Bring back stashed changes</td><td>Ctrl+V. It's back.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git reset --soft HEAD~1</td><td>Undo last commit, keep changes</td><td>Undo the save, but your edits are still there</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git reset --hard HEAD~1</td><td>Undo last commit AND revert files</td><td>Nuke it. Undo save + Ctrl+Z everything.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git revert abc123</td><td>New commit that undoes a previous one</td><td>Make a new save that undoes the damage. Transparently.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git merge --abort</td><td>Cancel a merge in progress</td><td>"Nope, undo everything, pretend this never happened"</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-group-header"><td colspan="3">Handy Extras</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git tag v1.0</td><td>Bookmark a specific version</td><td>Name it "FINAL_v2_APPROVED_USE_THIS_ONE.xlsx"</td></tr>
            <tr><td>.gitignore</td><td>Tell Git to ignore certain files</td><td>"Hey Excel, don't track my scratch sheets, okay?"</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git log --oneline</td><td>Compact version history</td><td>Version history but just the subject lines</td></tr>
            <tr><td>git remote -v</td><td>See which remote you're connected to</td><td>Checking which OneDrive folder this thing syncs to</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- ────────── KEY CONCEPTS ────────── -->
      <section id="key-concepts">
        <h2>Key concepts</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">These aren't commands, but they trip everyone up. Understanding them makes everything else click.</p>

        <div class="concept-grid">
          <div class="concept-card">
            <div class="concept-term">Working directory</div>
            <div class="concept-meaning">The files on your machine right now</div>
            <div class="concept-excel">The cells you're staring at and typing into right now. This is your desk.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-card">
            <div class="concept-term">Staging area</div>
            <div class="concept-meaning">Changes you've selected with <code>git add</code> but haven't committed</div>
            <div class="concept-excel">You've highlighted cells but haven't hit save yet. They're in limbo.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-card">
            <div class="concept-term">Committed</div>
            <div class="concept-meaning">Saved in Git's history &mdash; safe and recoverable</div>
            <div class="concept-excel">It's in version history. You can always get it back. Breathe.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-card">
            <div class="concept-term">Uncommitted</div>
            <div class="concept-meaning">Only exists on your machine right now &mdash; fragile</div>
            <div class="concept-excel">Unsaved edits. Close the window and they vanish into the void.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-card">
            <div class="concept-term">HEAD</div>
            <div class="concept-meaning">The commit you're currently looking at</div>
            <div class="concept-excel">Whichever version you currently have open. That's HEAD.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-card">
            <div class="concept-term">Origin</div>
            <div class="concept-meaning">The default name for your remote server (usually GitHub)</div>
            <div class="concept-excel">The OneDrive folder where the shared copy lives. That's your origin.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-card">
            <div class="concept-term">main / master</div>
            <div class="concept-meaning">The primary branch</div>
            <div class="concept-excel">The original Sheet1 &mdash; the one everyone treats as the source of truth. Don't mess with it directly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ────────── REAL STORIES ────────── -->
      <section id="stories">
        <h2>Real stories</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">Step-by-step walkthroughs of everyday situations. Pick the one that matches what you're trying to do.</p>

        <div class="story-card">
          <h4>"I just joined the team and need to start working"</h4>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">1</span><span class="story-text"><code>git clone https://github.com/team/project</code> — download the project</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">2</span><span class="story-text"><code>git checkout -b my-feature</code> — create your own branch to work on</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">3</span><span class="story-text">Make your changes (edit files like normal)</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">4</span><span class="story-text"><code>git add .</code> then <code>git commit -m "Add login page"</code> — save your work</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">5</span><span class="story-text"><code>git push -u origin my-feature</code> — upload it so your team can see</span></div>
          <div class="story-excel">Grab the shared workbook, duplicate a tab so you don't wreck the original, make your edits, save, upload. Day one, done.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="story-card">
          <h4>"I was working on something but need to switch tasks urgently"</h4>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">1</span><span class="story-text"><code>git stash</code> — set aside your half-done work</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">2</span><span class="story-text"><code>git switch main</code> — go back to main</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">3</span><span class="story-text">Do the urgent fix, commit, push</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">4</span><span class="story-text"><code>git switch my-feature</code> — go back to your branch</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">5</span><span class="story-text"><code>git stash pop</code> — bring back your half-done work</span></div>
          <div class="story-excel">Ctrl+X your half-done work, switch tabs, put out the fire, switch back, Ctrl+V. Crisis handled, nothing lost.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="story-card">
          <h4>"I committed something I shouldn't have"</h4>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">1</span><span class="story-text">If you haven't pushed yet: <code>git reset --soft HEAD~1</code> — undo the commit, keep your files</span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">2</span><span class="story-text">Fix what was wrong, then <code>git add .</code> + <code>git commit -m "Fixed version"</code></span></div>
          <div class="story-step"><span class="story-num">3</span><span class="story-text">If you already pushed: <code>git revert abc123</code> — create a new commit that undoes the bad one</span></div>
          <div class="story-excel">Just saved? Undo the save, your edits are still there, fix and re-save. Already on the shared drive? Don't delete history &mdash; make a new save that undoes the damage.</div>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /content -->
